<subSubSection id="48D355CA8E83FF0D48F756B8FB95FE04" pageId="205" pageNumber="206" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="007606418E83FF0D48F756B8FB95FE04" blockId="205.[151,1436,151,2001]" pageId="205" pageNumber="206">
Remarks. This species belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="C7C97DC28E83FF0D4A7D56B8FD40FE5C" authorityName="R. Perkins" authorityYear="1907" box="[589,741,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Dryinidae" genus="Deinodryinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="205" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538E83FF0D4A7D56B8FD40FE5C" box="[589,741,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="205" pageNumber="206">Deinodryinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because its enlarged claw has one long bristle situated further distally than proximal prominence (Plate 56C). It was described for mistake in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="C7C97DC28E83FF0D4CAB5694FB4FFE20" authorityName="Jurine" authorityYear="1807" box="[1179,1258,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Dryinidae" genus="Anteon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="205" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="32BDDA538E83FF0D4CAB5694FB4FFE20" box="[1179,1258,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="205" pageNumber="206">Anteon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whose species have one bristle located directly on the proximal prominence of the enlarged claw.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
